  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Celebrating the Pacification of Shu
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Emperor holds dominion and caresses the Nine Provinces,
    So that the Middle Kingdom dwells secure.
    With discipline the armies march forth complete,
    And sweep away all base rebellion.
    Wherever the tidings of victory reach,
    Joy ascends and pervades all hearts.

    With reverence I contemplate—ah, you understand—
    Endowed with the sage-like virtue of Yao and Shun,
    Undertaking the righteous campaigns of Yin and Zhou,
    Rising from river and lake, crossing through Chu and Yue,
    Every direction yields before your advance.
    You pacify Qi and Lu, sweep clear the clouds of Yan,
    Everywhere people celebrate your triumph.
    Great achievements accumulate, and
    Corrupted customs are made anew.
    Men find their hearths, women their homes,
    All dwell in peace.
    Writing becomes uniform, carriages run on one gauge—
    Who dare not offer congratulations?

    Yet that land of Shu presumed to steal a name,
    Trusting in its treacherous cliffs, defying your command.
    How could they not know
    That a mantis raises its arm against a wheel?
    Virtue proclaims their guilt, and punishment falls—
    As swift as setting goose feathers ablaze.
    The Sword Gorge's path grows smooth again,
    The Whirlpool's waters settle calm.

    This springs from Heaven's unfolding design,
    From your sage counsel's resolute will alone.
    Such swift unity is rare in all antiquity.

    I, your humble minister, am blessed to witness this glorious age,
    Already hearing victory songs in my ears.
    Though I guard my modest post with diligence,
    How could I forget the grace of this restoration?
    With reverent bow I offer praise,
    And humbly present ten thousand years of blessings.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Nine Provinces' refers to ancient China as a unified whole.
  - key: ''
    value: Yao and Shun represent the ideal sage-rulers of antiquity.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Yin and Zhou campaigns evokes the historical precedent for righteous military campaigns.
  - key: ''
    value: The mantis and wheel is a classical metaphor for futile resistance against overwhelming force.
  - key: ''
    value: The Sword Gorge (劍閣) and Whirlpool (灔澦堆) are geographical features of Shu that symbolize its former inaccessibility.
